Center selection by iteration

Note that in some configurations the number of centers decreases with respect to the previous iteration, even though the probability increases. This is due to the decrease in the number of uncovered nodes from which we sample the centers. Suppose that in one iteration the probability of selecting a center is 0.05 and there are 5000 uncovered nodes: the expected number of centers will be 250. If in the next iterations there are just 1000 uncovered nodes, and the probability of selecting a center is 0.1, the expected number of centers will be 100.
